  <div class="box">
    <div class="box-label">On Training Days vs. Rest Days</div>
    <div class="box-text">On training days, eat all 4 meals including the post-workout shake. On rest days, you can skip the post-workout meal and redistribute those calories across your other 3 meals — or just eat slightly less overall. A 150–200 kcal reduction on rest days is fine and creates a slightly deeper weekly deficit without feeling restrictive day to day.</div>
  </div>

  <div class="box slate">
    <div class="box-label">The Three Things That Wreck This Plan</div>
    <div class="box-text">
      <strong>Liquid calories you're not tracking:</strong> One flavored coffee, two glasses of wine, or a sports drink can silently add 400–600 kcal to your day. Track everything that has calories — including drinks.<br><br>
      <strong>Eating too little:</strong> Going below 1,600 kcal to lose faster kills training performance, tanks energy, and causes muscle loss. Slow is sustainable. Fast is temporary.<br><br>
      <strong>Inconsistent weekends:</strong> Five days of discipline erased by two untracked days. You don't have to be perfect on weekends — but you need to stay aware. One off-plan meal is fine. An entire off-plan weekend is not.
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="box teal">
    <div class="box-label">Easy Swaps That Keep the Macros Intact</div>
    <div class="box-text">
      <strong>Don't like chicken?</strong> Swap for ground turkey, canned tuna, or shrimp — same protein range.<br>
      <strong>Hate eggs?</strong> Replace with a protein shake + a slice of whole wheat toast.<br>
      <strong>Can't eat dairy?</strong> Use a plant-based protein powder and swap Greek yogurt for silken tofu blended with fruit.<br>
      <strong>Need more volume?</strong> Add a second serving of vegetables to any meal — they're nearly free calories and keep you full.<br><br>
      <em style="color:#999;">The foods are flexible. The targets — 2,200 kcal and 180g protein — are not.</em>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

